      section
        h2.bullets What is A "Web" Standard?  
        ul
          li A Mix Of Standards (JS) & Recommendations (HTML/CSS)
          li Not All Standards Are Equal
          li
            hr
          li 
            strong Standard Bodies
          li W3C, IETF, ISO, ECMA, Unicode Consortium, IANA
          li Tries To Get Vendors To Agree
          li Standards Making Is Slow Process...
        aside
          pre
            |What is a standrd. In this context standards refer to how browsers should render HTML, CSS
            |when you say width="100px" the standard 'recommends' exactly what this should do (More on this on a moment).            
            <br>
            |Note w3c does not publish strict standards but rather strong recommendations. This is true for HTML & CSS and differs
            |from ECMA. Standards for programming languages are much stricter and should be thought of as rules not recommendation.
            <br>
            |A js interpreter is expected to adhere to the ECMA standard, browsers area a little looser. They often integrate
            |features before they are 'published' by the W3C.


      section
        h2.bullets How Do Things Become Standards?
        ul
          li 
            strong For W3C Generally
          li Working Draft
          li Candidate Recommendation
          li Proposed Recommendation
          li W3C Recommendation
          li But They Work - XMLHttpRequest & WebRTC   
          li Slow! HTML5 'Started' in 2008, Stable Recommendation Expected 2014! 
        aside 
          pre
            |So we have a way of formulating the rules. And the advantages to following the rules
            |are what's described in the manifesto. Interoperability - non Proprietary standards.
            <br>
            |But what happens when you do not follow the rules.                  


      section
